    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-03-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-03-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="801"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d801">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.24/942</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The American Counselor of Embassy for Economic Affairs</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Butrick</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Chilean Assistant Secretary of Economy and
                        Commerce</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Heatley</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="92" xml:id="d801fn92">Copy transmitted to the Department hy
                        the Ambassador in Chile in his despatch No. 6026, March 22; received April
                        6.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-03-20">March 20,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Heatley</hi>: I am pleased to acknowledge the
                    receipt of your courteous confidential note no. 13<note n="93" xml:id="d801fn93"
                        >Not printed.</note> of the Department General of Economic Policy of the
                    sixth instant, confirming our conversations <pb facs="0847" n="835"
                        xml:id="pg_835"/> regarding the supplying of copper, and communicating to me
                    that for the duration of the present world conflict the Ministry of Economy and
                    Commerce will subject the copper export negotiations to certain conditions
                    indicated in your note under reference without prejudice to the provisions
                    established in Decree No. 64 Bis of February 3, of the current year.<note n="94"
                        xml:id="d801fn94">See despatch No. 5944, March 10, from the Ambassador in
                        Chile, <ref target="#pg_832">p. 832</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In accordance with the agreement, I am today sending to the Ministry of Foreign
                    Relations of Chile and to the Department of State at Washington, a copy of your
                    courteous note and of this one.</p>
                <p>Very sincerely [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Richard P. Butrick</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
